commentBody:
@Shrike
I'm reading Hyperion by Dan Simmons, and your name unnerves me.

Anyway, I knew it couldn't have been meals, because Meals on Wheels is capitalized, and the wheels in the clue wasn't. I thought it was a decent clue for a Tuesday: wheels and DEALS.

@Shrike

Clues asking for a partner are usually looking for a phrase of the form “[clue] _and_ ANSWER”. “Meals _on_ Wheels” doesn’t fit, whereas “wheels _and_ deals” does. 
And, as Katie points out, “wheels” wasn’t capitalised as it would need to be for Meals on Wheels

@Steve L

You got me.  The only thing I know about rugby is that I didn't ever want to play it, and they use weird words.  Made up words.

Unlike baseball and football, all of whose words are entirely organically produced.

@John

Brooke Husic's Monday New Yorker crossword took me longer than most Saturday NYT puzzles, and that included checking a few answers when I got stuck. I also had to set it aside a while, which I never do with the NYT puzzles.

Or you could do Christina Iverson's Sunday LAT puzzle. I really enjoyed the theme, and so did a few friends I recommended it to.

@Niki B

HAR!!!

😂😘😂

@Marshall Walthew

Thanks for the recommendation! I like both Nirvana and Patti Smith, but I don't think I've heard that. 

I have a vague memory of Tori Amos covering that song. But having looked it up on secondhandsongs.com, I kinda wonder who *hasn't* covered it?

@john ezra and @Andy
Yep, I got the puzzle quickly but had to come here to get the theme. 
And I don't agree with Sam that it's "pair o." Just say "para" before each pair.

@Spelling Marauder

See? That’s the tricky part!

I sort of thought that I had them reversed when I wrote that. The funny thing is that I put the correct entry in the puzzle (correctly spelled) without really thinking about it.

@Mike
I think I remember "gelid" from a past Spelling Bee.
Speaking of which, why isn't "capacitate" accepted in today's Bee?

@Mark

I couldn't resist the urge to tack that on to my Diary of a Crossword Fiend review.

My parents had that album when I was in grade school. I think my sibs and I listened to it more than they did.

@Valerie

Ian Livengood has had 84 puzzles reviewed by Diary of a Crossword Fiend, which covers NYT, LAT, WSJ and other publications. Sorry that I don't know where his puzzles have appeared, but if you go to the DoaCF site, there's a place where you can search the constructor tags. 

On behalf of constructors and constructor wannabes everywhere, thanks for noticing the byline of a constructor you like and for wanting to see more of their work.

@Valerie

Thanks! I appreciate your taking the time to let me know. 

And I hope you find some more of Ian Livengood’s puzzles that you enjoy.

@Francis

Glad you enjoyed it!

She's a hoot, and I just love the way it leads up to them jamming "ABC."

@Nora

I never caught the camera shake, even after re-watching it, maybe because it's on a tiny phone screen. 

"The earth just moved" did seem out of place, but now it makes total sense. Thanks!

@sotto voce

Thanks! The Allan Sherman song takes me way back.

I didn’t delve into the reason behind New Hampshire’s lack of a seatbelt law, but I expected it was what you found.

@Rachel
I can’t say what I’d really like to about this, the emus would strike me down.

Thank goodness I’m shown there are many wonderful, sane citizens out there through Wordplay comments.

@Gabe
Lade, laden with guilt, bill of lading, ladle all kinna mean the same thing.
Words that end in "id" commonly turn a noun into its adjective.

@Gabe
This is what speaks to me regarding lade(s,n)
"Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest."

@Andrew Kennelly

I learned gelid in the NYT Spelling Bee.
Surprised that I remembered it.

@James
I would hazard that they both approximate to “perra” with a New York twang. 

As an ex-pat Scot I vividly remember an elementary teacher telling me my pronunciation of “of” was misleading my children.

@RozzieGrandma
In my one time part of Scotland “of” and “off” are one and the same although the vowel sound is probably a bit longer than an American ear might expect. 
In thirty years the vocabulary has had to change but the accent is much the same.

@Helen Wright

I’m sorry to hear about your friend. I know it’s been a while, but that kind of thing stays with you forever, doesn’t it? 

(I woke up about 1 AM inexplicably thinking about how my younger sister was killed; she was hit by a car while crossing a street at night.)

@Helen Wright
I agree with you, but legislation seldom solves such problems. Responsible individuals don't need laws to instinctively do what's right.

I'm being good today, so I hope that didn't come across a bit terse. 😉

@Jerry
You are all sweetness and light today 🥰 Hope I am too.

I agree with your thoughts. However, when it comes to road safety it’s not always a lack of responsibility that causes issues. Accidents do happen. My friend’s Mum did nothing wrong; I’m told the other driver had a medical event which caused the crash. She lost both her girls because belts weren’t compulsory or deemed necessary at that time.

@Andrzej

It may make it bad for you but not overall bad because it actually makes sense to people who are familiar with the different pronunciations.  In the US, if you know people from around the country, you would certainly have heard it pronounced that way.

It's kind of like when you don't know a word.  The inclusion of that word in a puzzle does not make for a bad puzzle.

@Warren

Or

<a href="https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=EMoi_m2G6XU" target="_blank">https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=EMoi_m2G6XU</a>

@Jane Wheelaghan

I'm slowly sneaking up on how it works. There's a minor character in "Yellowstone" who speaks in an accent the Montanans affect not to understand, and which I don't understand. But she pronounces "bear" like "baar". Add to that the AmE pronunciation of "o'" (=of) with an "ah" sound, rather than a schwa or "owe" sound, and I can begin to hear it in my head. 
It still sounds bizarre when I speak it aloud, though, and it's something I've had to figure out in retrospect---no way was it coming to mind while solving.

@RozzieGrandma

I think the benzene ring is why I glommed onto the theme right away.  The puns about the ortho and para position on the ring informed me from long ago.

In fact, it was almost second nature to me.  I knew it immediately when I saw DICEDICE. And I was surprised when others found it hard to discern.

@The X-Phile 
Man, they get a LOT of mileage out of a joke!
(And a hard boiled egg.)

@The X-Phile

I see what you did there. :-)

But PARA and "pair o'" are actually closer together in Scottish Standard English than they are in the Received Pronunciation of the Oxford English Dictionary.

@Roger

Interesting, because those two sound the same to me. 

The word paradox sounds like a pair a docks.

@Oikofuge
You mean, there's a difference? 
;-)

@JohnWM

The International Phonetic Alphabet was invented so that we *could* have written discussion of accents. And I'm pleased that, despite its otherwise user-belligerent interface, this site supports the IPA character set. 

Not many folk here take advantage of that, though.

@JohnWM
Or we can both listen to the same intermediary:
<a href="https://www.ipachart.com" target="_blank">https://www.ipachart.com</a>/

@HJ
I guess we look at Lloyd's "giant" descriptor, when "recognizable" might be more appropriate. We know Lloyd's to insure celebrity body parts, etc. Maybe that makes them a giant?

Eh, NYSE could very well be, as you elude to. They certainly attract, facilitate and cater to Finance giants. Tomato, tomahto.

@Jerry My pedantry is not necessarily against the fact Lloyd's is hugely important and recognisable part of the insurance industry, in that sense it is giant. It's more the language of calling a marketplace A GIANT...
It's the turn of phrase I do not think is quite right. 
NYSE certainly does represent something huge, but again not sure it's the right language one would use to describe it.

@Diana

If you find out the answer, let me know!

I can imagine a pronunciation of paralegal that doesn’t hit the A quite as hard as pay or paper — but it’s still a long A.

@Susan E

Thanks. 

My third grade teacher (the wonderful Mrs. Terrier) didn't teach me about r-controlled vowels. In fact, no one did.

@Jay

Thanks for mentioning Meals on Wheels (a useful program). 

I knew GELID, so DEALS was obviously correct. But having reread the clue, I can see where mEALS made sense.

@kilaueabart

Just a propos of nothing much, Lloyd is originally Welsh, the even more daunting Llwyd.
Lots of double l's in Welsh, indicating a voiceless alveolar lateral fricative. (Though the English name "Lloyd" is just pronounced with a simple "L" sound.)

@Francis

Welsh W is always a vowel. There are seven Welsh vowels, A,E,I,O,U,W,Y. 
W takes care of the "oo" sounds.

@Oikofuge

I came to the comments to see voiceless alveolar lateral fricative - and I wasn’t disappointed. 😻

Delightful!

@Nick

... a chance to learn two words? 

I didn't know ASSAI, but now I do.

@Convoid-04 I used to love reading about the logical fallacies so I got mad at myself for missing the meaning of DOCKS DOCKS. Must have been a great one to understand without help.
Thanks for the stretch and congrats on your debut!
Hopefully we’ll see more from you, Ingrid Steffensen!
